03913nam a22005295i 9780774850360DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072002xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748503607 a10.59962/97807748503602doi  a(DE-B1597)661963  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aUA600 ǂb R53 2002eb 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a355/.0330711 aRichter, Andrew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAvoiding Armageddon :bCanadian Military Strategy and Nuclear Weapons, 1950-1963 /cAndrew Richter. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Canadian Military History00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tThe Defence and Security Environment, 1945-9 -- tCanada’s Air Defence Debate -- tCanadian Views on Nuclear Weapons and Related Issues of Strategy -- tThe Canadian Debate on the Acquisition of Nuclear Weapons -- tCanadian Conceptual Understanding of Arms Control -- tLinks between Canadian Strategic Thinking and Defence Policy, 1950-63 -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe advent of nuclear weapons in the 1940s brought enormous changes to doctrines regarding the use of force in resolving disputes. American strategists have been widely credited with most of these; Canadians, most have assumed, did not conduct their own strategic analysis. Avoiding Armageddon soundly debunks this notion. Drawing on previously classified government records, Richter reveals that Canadian defence officials did come to independent strategic understandings of the most critical issues of the nuclear age. Canadian appreciation of deterrence, arms control, and strategic stability differed conceptually from the US models. Similarly, Canadian thinking on the controversial issues of air defence and the domestic acquisition of nuclear weapons was primarily influenced by decidedly Canadian interests. Avoiding Armageddon is a work with far-reaching implications. It illustrates Canada's considerable latitude for independent defence thinking while providing key historical information that helps make sense of the contemporary Canadian defence debate.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485036040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774850360423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774850360/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles